      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt Registry"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A prompt registry is a versioned store for the prompts (system instructions, few-shot examples, and template variables) that define an LLM application's behavior. Prompts change independently of model weights — a registry decouples prompt iteration from model rollout and provides the same audit trail: which prompt version is in production, what its eval scores were, and how to roll back."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Without a registry, prompts live in application code or environment variables. That means prompt changes ride alongside code deploys, there is no immutable history, and a regression can only be traced back to a git diff rather than a named, evaluated artifact."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Registry Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Prompt Registry lifecycle from author to serving"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Authors commit prompt YAML to git. CI validates schema and runs regression tests; on pass it pushes the versioned artifact to the registry. The serving layer loads the production prompt by name at startup. Eval and monitoring tools record the prompt version with every request so regressions are traceable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
